nBeef Bourguignon
cBeef
d52904
iHeat a large casserole pan and add 1 tbsp goose fat.
iSeason the beef and fry until golden brown, about 3-5 mins, then turn over and fry the other side until the meat is browned all over, adding more fat if necessary.
iDo this in 2-3 batches, transferring the meat to a colander set over a bowl when browned.
iIn the same pan, fry the bacon, shallots or pearl onions, mushrooms, garlic and bouquet garni until lightly browned.
iMix in the tomato purée and cook for a few mins, stirring into the mixture.
iThis enriches the bourguignon and makes a great base for the stew.
iThen return the beef and any drained juices to the pan and stir through.
iPour over the wine and about 100ml water so the meat bobs up from the liquid, but isn’t completely covered.
iBring to the boil and use a spoon to scrape the caramelised cooking juices from the bottom of the pan – this will give the stew more flavour.
iHeat oven to 150C/fan 130C/gas 2.
iMake a cartouche: tear off a square of foil slightly larger than the casserole, arrange it in the pan so it covers the top of the stew and trim away any excess foil.
iThen cook for 3 hrs.
iIf the sauce looks watery, remove the beef and veg with a slotted spoon, and set aside.
iCook the sauce over a high heat for a few mins until the sauce has thickened a little, then return the beef and vegetables to the pan.
iTo make the celeriac mash, peel the celeriac and cut into cubes.
iHeat the olive oil in a large frying pan.
iTip in the celeriac and fry for 5 mins until it turns golden.
iSeason well with salt and pepper.
iStir in the rosemary, thyme, bay and cardamom pods, then pour over 200ml water, enough to nearly cover the celeriac.
iTurn the heat to low, partially cover the pan and leave to simmer for 25-30 mins.
iAfter 25-30 mins, the celeriac should be soft and most of the water will have evaporated.
iDrain away any remaining water, then remove the herb sprigs, bay and cardamom pods.
iLightly crush with a potato masher, then finish with a glug of olive oil and season to taste.
iSpoon the beef bourguignon into serving bowls and place a large spoonful of the celeriac mash on top.
iGarnish with one of the bay leaves, if you like.
