nBeef Brisket Pot Roast
cBeef
d52812
i1 Prepare the brisket for cooking: On one side of the brisket there should be a layer of fat, which you want.
iIf there are any large chunks of fat, cut them off and discard them.
iLarge pieces of fat will not be able to render out completely.
iUsing a sharp knife, score the fat in parallel lines, about 3/4-inch apart.
iSlice through the fat, not the beef.
iRepeat in the opposite direction to make a cross-hatch pattern.
iSalt the brisket well and let it sit at room temperature for 30 minutes.
i2 Sear the brisket: You'll need an oven-proof, thick-bottomed pot with a cover, or Dutch oven, that is just wide enough to hold the brisket roast with a little room for the onions.
iPat the brisket dry and place it, fatty side down, into the pot and place it on medium high heat.
iCook for 5-8 minutes, lightly sizzling, until the fat side is nicely browned.
i(If the roast seems to be cooking too fast, turn the heat down to medium.
iYou want a steady sizzle, not a raging sear.
iTurn the brisket over and cook for a few minutes more to brown the other side.
i3 Sauté the onions and garlic: When the brisket has browned, remove it from the pot and set aside.
iThere should be a couple tablespoons of fat rendered in the pot, if not, add some olive oil.
iAdd the chopped onions and increase the heat to high.
iSprinkle a little salt on the onions.
iSauté, stirring often, until the onions are lightly browned, 5-8 minutes.
iStir in the garlic and cook 1-2 more minutes.
i4 Return brisket to pot, add herbs, stock, bring to simmer, cover, cook in oven: Preheat the oven to 300°F.
iUse kitchen twine to tie together the bay leaves, rosemary and thyme.
iMove the onions and garlic to the sides of the pot and nestle the brisket inside.
iAdd the beef stock and the tied-up herbs.
iBring the stock to a boil on the stovetop.
iCover the pot, place the pot in the 300°F oven and cook for 3 hours.
iCarefully flip the brisket every hour so it cooks evenly.
i5 Add carrots, continue to cook: After 3 hours, add the carrots.
iCover the pot and cook for 1 hour more, or until the carrots are cooked through and the brisket is falling-apart tender.
i6 Remove brisket to cutting board, tent with foil: When the brisket is falling-apart tender, take the pot out of the oven and remove the brisket to a cutting board.
iCover it with foil.
iPull out and discard the herbs.
i7 Make sauce (optional): At this point you have two options.
iYou can serve as is, or you can make a sauce with the drippings and some of the onions.
iIf you serve as is, skip this step.
iTo make a sauce, remove the carrots and half of the onions, set aside and cover them with foil.
iPour the ingredients that are remaining into the pot into a blender, and purée until smooth.
iIf you want, add 1 tablespoon of mustard to the mix.
iPut into a small pot and keep warm.
i8 Slice the meat across the grain: Notice the lines of the muscle fibers of the roast.
iThis is the "grain" of the meat.
iSlice the meat perpendicular to these lines, or across the grain (cutting this way further tenderizes the meat), in 1/4-inch to 1/2-inch slices.
iServe with the onions, carrots and gravy.
iServe with mashed, roasted or boiled potatoes, egg noodles or polenta.
