nJamaican Beef Patties
cBeef
d52938
iTo a large bowl, add flour, 1 teaspoon salt, and turmeric and mix thoroughly.
iRub shortening into flour until there are small pieces of shortening completely covered with flour.
iPour in 1/2 cup of the ice water and mix with your hands to bring the dough together.
iKeep adding ice water 2 to 3 tablespoons at a time until the mixture forms a dough.
iAt this stage, you can cut the dough into 2 large pieces, wrap in plastic and refrigerate for 30 minutes before using it.
iAlternatively, cut the dough into 10 to 12 equal pieces, place on a platter or baking sheet, cover securely with plastic wrap and let chill for 30 minutes while you make the filling.
iAdd ground beef to a large bowl.
iSprinkle in allspice and black pepper.
iMix together and set aside.
iHeat oil in a skillet until hot.
iAdd onions and sauté until translucent.
iAdd hot pepper, garlic and thyme and continue to sauté for another minute.
iAdd 1/4 teaspoon salt.
iAdd seasoned ground beef and toss to mix, breaking up any clumps, and let cook until the meat is no longer pink.
iAdd ketchup and more salt to taste.
iPour in 2 cups of water and stir.
iBring the mixture to a boil then reduce heat and let simmer until most of the liquid has evaporated and whatever is remaining has reduced to a thick sauce.
iFold in green onions.
iRemove from heat and let cool completely.
iBeat the egg and water together to make an egg wash.
iSet aside.
iNow you can prepare the dough in two ways.
iFirst Method: Flour the work surface and rolling pin.
iIf you had cut it into 2 large pieces, then take one of the large pieces and roll it out into a very large circle.
iTake a bowl with a wide rim (about 5 inches) and cut out three circles.
iPlace about 3 heaping tablespoons of the filling onto 1/2 of each circle.
iDip a finger into the water and moisten the edges of the pastry.
iFold over the other half and press to seal.
iTake a fork and crimp the edges.
iCut off any extra to make it look neat and uniform.
iPlace on a parchment-lined baking sheet and continue to work until you have rolled all the dough and filled the patties.
iSecond Method: If you had pre-cut the dough into individual pieces, work with one piece of dough at a time.
iRoll it out on a floured surface into a 5-inch circle or a little larger.
iDon’t worry if the edges are not perfect.
iPlace 3 heaping tablespoons of the filling on one side of the circle.
iDip a finger into the water and moisten the edges of the pastry.
iFold over the other half and press to seal.
iTake a fork and crimp the edges.
iCut off any extra to make it look neat and uniform.
iPlace on a parchment-lined baking sheet and continue work until you have rolled all the dough and filled the patties.
iAfter forming the patties, place the pans in the refrigerator while you heat the oven to 350 F.
iJust before adding the pans with the patties to the oven, brush the patties with egg wash.
iBake patties for 30 minutes or until golden brown.
iCool on wire racks.
iServe warm.
