nMontreal Smoked Meat
cBeef
d52927
iTo make the cure, in a small bowl mix together salt, pink salt, black pepper, coriander, sugar, bay leaf, and cloves.
iCoat entire brisket with the cure and place in an extra-large resealable plastic bag.
iPlace in the coldest part of the refrigerator and cure for 4 days, flipping brisket twice a day.
iRemove brisket from bag and wash as much cure off as possible under cold running water.
iPlace brisket in a large container and fill with water and let soak for 2 hours, replacing water every 30 minutes.
iRemove from water and pat dry with paper towels.
iTo make the rub, mix together black pepper, coriander, paprika, garlic powder, onion powder, dill weed, mustard, celery seed, and crushed red papper in a small bowl.
iCoat entire brisket with the rub.
iFire up smoker or grill to 225 degrees, adding chunks of smoking wood chunks when at temperature.
iWhen wood is ignited and producing smoke, place brisket in, fat side up, and smoke until an instant read thermometer registers 165 degrees when inserted into thickest part of the brisket, about 6 hours.
iTransfer brisket to large roasting pan with V-rack.
iPlace roasting pan over two burners on stovetop and fill with 1-inch of water.
iBring water to a boil over high heat, reduce heat to medium, cover roasting pan with aluminum foil, and steam brisket until an instant read thermometer registers 180 degrees when inserted into thickest part of the meat, 1 to 2 hours, adding more hot water as needed.
iTransfer brisket to cutting board and let cool slightly.
iSlice and serve, preferably on rye with mustard.
