nCoq au vin
cChicken
d52832
iHeat 1 tbsp of the oil in a large, heavy-based saucepan or flameproof dish.
iTip in the bacon and fry until crisp.
iRemove and drain on kitchen paper.
iAdd the shallots to the pan and fry, stirring or shaking the pan often, for 5-8 mins until well browned all over.
iRemove and set aside with the bacon.
iPat the chicken pieces dry with kitchen paper.
iPour the remaining oil into the pan, then fry half the chicken pieces, turning regularly, for 5-8 mins until well browned.
iRemove, then repeat with the remaining chicken.
iRemove and set aside.
iScatter in the garlic and fry briefly, then, with the heat medium-high, pour in the brandy or Cognac, stirring the bottom of the pan to deglaze.
iThe alcohol should sizzle and start to evaporate so there is not much left.
iReturn the chicken legs and thighs to the pan along with any juices, then pour in a little of the wine, stirring the bottom of the pan again.
iStir in the rest of the wine, the stock and tomato purée, drop in the bouquet garni, season with pepper and a pinch of salt, then return the bacon and shallots to the pan.
iCover, lower the heat to a gentle simmer, add the chicken breasts and cook for 50 mins-1hr.
iJust before ready to serve, heat the oil for the mushrooms in a large non-stick frying pan.
iAdd the mushrooms and fry over a high heat for a few mins until golden.
iRemove and keep warm.
iLift the chicken, shallots and bacon from the pan and transfer to a warmed serving dish.
iRemove the bouquet garni.
iTo make the thickener, mix the flour, olive oil and butter in a small bowl using the back of a teaspoon.
iBring the wine mixture to a gentle boil, then gradually drop in small pieces of the thickener, whisking each piece in using a wire whisk.
iSimmer for 1-2 mins.
iScatter the mushrooms over the chicken, then pour over the wine sauce.
iGarnish with chopped parsley.
