nJerk chicken with rice & peas
cChicken
d52937
iTo make the jerk marinade, combine all the ingredients in a food processor along with 1 tsp salt, and blend to a purée.
iIf you’re having trouble getting it to blend, just keep turning off the blender, stirring the mixture, and trying again.
iEventually it will start to blend up – don’t be tempted to add water, as you want a thick paste.
iTaste the jerk mixture for seasoning – it should taste pretty salty, but not unpleasantly, puckering salty.
iYou can now throw in more chillies if it’s not spicy enough for you.
iIf it tastes too salty and sour, try adding in a bit more brown sugar until the mixture tastes well balanced.
iMake a few slashes in the chicken thighs and pour the marinade over the meat, rubbing it into all the crevices.
iCover and leave to marinate overnight in the fridge.
iIf you want to barbecue your chicken, get the coals burning 1 hr or so before you’re ready to cook.
iAuthentic jerked meats are not exactly grilled as we think of grilling, but sort of smoke-grilled.
iTo get a more authentic jerk experience, add some wood chips to your barbecue, and cook your chicken over slow, indirect heat for 30 mins.
iTo cook in the oven, heat to 180C/160C fan/gas 4.
iPut the chicken pieces in a roasting tin with the lime halves and cook for 45 mins until tender and cooked through.
iWhile the chicken is cooking, prepare the rice & peas.
iRinse the rice in plenty of cold water, then tip it into a large saucepan with all the remaining ingredients except the kidney beans.
iSeason with salt, add 300ml cold water and set over a high heat.
iOnce the rice begins to boil, turn it down to a medium heat, cover and cook for 10 mins.
iAdd the beans to the rice, then cover with a lid.
iLeave off the heat for 5 mins until all the liquid is absorbed.
iSqueeze the roasted lime over the chicken and serve with the rice & peas, and some hot sauce if you like it really spicy.
