nBlackberry Fool
cDessert
d52891
iFor the biscuits, preheat the oven to 200C/180C (fan)/Gas 6 and line two large baking trays with baking parchment.
iScatter the nuts over a baking tray and roast in the oven for 6-8 minutes, or until golden-brown.
iWatch them carefully so that they don’t have a chance to burn.
iRemove from the oven, tip onto a board and leave to cool.
iPut the butter and sugar in a large bowl and beat with a wooden spoon until light and creamy.
iRoughly chop the cooled nuts and add to the creamed butter and sugar, along with the lemon zest, flour and baking powder.
iStir well until the mixture comes together and forms a ball – you may need to use your hands.
iDivide the biscuit dough into 24 even pieces and roll into small balls.
iPlace the balls the prepared baking trays, spaced well apart to allow for spreading.
iPress the biscuits to flatten to around 1cm/½in thick.
iBake the biscuits, one tray at a time, for 12 minutes or until very pale golden-brown.
iLeave to cool on the trays.
iThey will be very soft when you take them out of the oven, but will crisp as they cool.
iStore in an airtight tin and eat within five days.
iFor the fool, rinse the blackberries in a colander to wash away any dust or dirt.
iPut the blackberries in a non-stick saucepan and sprinkle over the caster sugar.
iStir in the lemon juice and heat gently for two minutes, or until the blackberries begin to soften and release their juices.
iRemove and reserve 12 blackberries for decoration and continue cooking the rest.
iSimmer the blackberries very gently for 15 minutes, stirring regularly until very soft and squidgy.
iRemove from the heat and press the berries and juice through a sieve over a bowl, using the bottom of a ladle to help you extract as much of the purée as possible.
iLeave the purée to cool and discard the seeds.
iYou should end up with around 325ml/11fl oz of purée.
iPut the cream and yoghurt in a large bowl and whip with an electric whisk until soft peaks form when the whisk is removed from the bowl – the acidity of the fruit will thicken the cream further, so don’t take it too far.
iWhen the purée is completely cold, adjust the sweetness to taste by adding more sugar if needed.
iPour it into the bowl with the whipped cream and yoghurt and stir just once or twice until very lightly combined.
iSpoon the blackberry fool into individual wide, glass dishes – or one large, single bowl.
iIt should look quite marbled, so don’t over-stir it.
iScatter a few tiny mint leaves on top and decorate with the reserved blackberries.
iSprinkle with a little sugar if you like and serve with the hazelnut biscuits.
