nChelsea Buns
cDessert
d52898
iSift the flour and salt into a large bowl.
iMake a well in the middle and add the yeast.
iMeanwhile, warm the milk and butter in a saucepan until the butter melts and the mixture is lukewarm.
iAdd the milk mixture and egg to the flour mixture and stir until the contents of the bowl come together as a soft dough.
i(You may need to add a little extra flour.
iTip the dough onto a generously floured work surface.
iKnead for five minutes, adding more flour if necessary, until the dough is smooth and elastic and no longer feels sticky.
iLightly oil a bowl with a little of the vegetable oil.
iPlace the dough into the bowl and turn until it is covered in the oil.
iCover the bowl with cling film and set aside in a warm place for one hour, or until the dough has doubled in size.
iLightly grease a baking tray.
iFor the filling, knock the dough back to its original size and turn out onto a lightly floured work surface.
iRoll the dough out into a rectangle 0.
i5cm/¼in thick.
iBrush all over with the melted butter, then sprinkle over the brown sugar, cinnamon and dried fruit.
iRoll the dough up into a tight cylinder , cut ten 4cm/1½in slice and place them onto a lightly greased baking sheet, leaving a little space between each slice.
iCover with a tea towel and set aside to rise for 30 minutes.
iPreheat oven to 190C/375F/Gas 5.
iBake the buns in the oven for 20-25 minutes, or until risen and golden-brown.
iMeanwhile, for the glaze, heat the milk and sugar in a saucepan until boiling.
iReduce the heat and simmer for 2-3 minutes.
iRemove the buns from the oven and brush with the glaze, then set aside to cool on a wire rack.
