nChoc Chip Pecan Pie
cDessert
d52856
iFirst, make the pastry.
iTip the ingredients into a food processor with 1 /4 tsp salt.
iBlend until the mixture resembles breadcrumbs.
iDrizzle 2-3 tsp cold water into the funnel while the blade is running – the mixture should start to clump together.
iTip onto a work surface and bring together, kneading briefly into a ball.
iPat into a disc, wrap in cling film, and chill for at least 20 mins.
iHeat oven to 200C/180C fan/gas 6.
iRemove the pastry from the fridge and leave at room temperature for 5 mins to soften.
iFlour the work surface, then unwrap the pastry and roll to a circle the thickness of a £1 coin.
iUse the pastry to line a deep, 23cm round fluted tin – mine was about 3cm deep.
iPress the pastry into the corners and up the sides, making sure there are no gaps.
iLeave 1cm pastry overhanging (save some of the pastry scraps for later).
iLine with baking parchment (scrunch it up first to make it more pliable) and fill with baking beans.
iBlind-bake for 15-20 mins until the sides are set, then remove the parchment and beans and return to the oven for 5 mins until golden brown.
iTrim the pastry so it’s flush with the top of the tin – a small serrated knife is best for this.
iIf there are any cracks, patch them up with the pastry scraps.
iMeanwhile, weigh the butter, syrup and sugars into a pan, and add 1 /4 tsp salt.
iHeat until the butter has melted and the sugar dissolved, stirring until smooth.
iRemove from the heat and cool for 10 mins.
iReduce oven to 160C/140C fan/gas 3.
iBeat the eggs in a bowl.
iAdd the syrup mixture, vanilla and pecans, and mix until well combined.
iPour half the mixture into the tart case, scatter over half the chocolate chips, then cover with the remaining filling and chocolate chips.
iBake on the middle shelf for 50-55 mins until set.
iRemove from the oven and leave to cool, then chill for at least 2 hrs before serving.
