nDundee cake
cDessert
d52899
iPut the almonds into a small bowl and pour over boiling water to just cover.
iLeave for 5 mins then drain in a sieve and leave to dry.
iPreheat the oven to 180C/160 C fan/Gas Mark 4.
iLine a deep loose-based 20cm cake tin with baking parchment.
iPut the butter in a large bowl and beat well until soft.
iAdd the sugar and beat until light and fluffy.
iStir in the orange zest and apricot jam.
iSieve together the flour and baking powder.
iAdd the eggs to the creamed butter and sugar, a little at a time, beating well between each addition.
iIf the mixture starts to curdle, stir in a little flour.
iAdd the remaining flour and ground almonds and mix well.
iMix in the milk and then add the dried fruit and cherries and mix gently together.
iSpoon the mixture into the prepared tin and spread level using the back of a spoon.
iArrange the whole almonds close together in neat circles on the top of the cake.
iBake in the oven for 45 mins.
iLower the oven temperature to 160C/140 C fan/Gas Mark 3 and cook for a further 60–80 minutes.
iCheck the cake after 50 minutes by inserting a wooden or metal skewer into the cake.
iWhen it’s done it should have just a few crumbs attached.
iCheck every 10 minutes - it’s important not to overcook this cake so the centre will be a little soft.
iWhen cooked, remove the cake briefly from the oven, put the milk and sugar into a small pan and heat gently until the sugar has dissolved.
iBrush over the top of the cake and return the cake to the oven for 2-3 mins.
iRemove and allow the cake to cool in the tin.
iWhen quite cold remove from the tin and wrap in foil and keep for at least 2 days before cutting.
