nEccles Cakes
cDessert
d52888
iTo make the pastry, dice the butter and put it in the freezer to go really hard.
iTip flour into the bowl of a food processor with half the butter and pulse to the texture of breadcrumbs.
iPour in the lemon juice and 100ml iced water, and pulse to a dough.
iTip in the rest of the butter and pulse a few times until the dough is heavily flecked with butter.
iIt is important that you don’t overdo this as the flecks of butter are what makes the pastry flaky.
iOn a floured surface roll the pastry out to a neat rectangle about 20 x 30cm.
iFold the two ends of the pastry into the middle (See picture 1), then fold in half (pic 2).
iRoll the pastry out again and refold the same way 3 more times resting the pastry for at least 15 mins each time between roll and fold, then leave to rest in the fridge for at least 30 mins before using.
iTo make the filling, melt the butter in a large saucepan.
iTake it off the heat and stir in all the other ingredients until completely mixed, then set aside.
iTo make the cakes, roll the pastry out until it’s just a little thicker than a £1 coin and cut out 8 rounds about 12cm across.
iRe-roll the trimming if needed.
iPlace a good heaped tablespoon of mixture in the middle of each round, brush the edges of the rounds with water, then gather the pastry around the filling and squeeze it together (pic 3).
iFlip them over so the smooth top is upwards and pat them into a smooth round.
iFlatten each round with a rolling pin to an oval until the fruit just starts to poke through, then place on a baking tray.
iCut 2 little slits in each Eccles cakes, brush generously with egg white and sprinkle with the sugar (pic 4).
iHeat the oven to 220C/200C fan/gas 8.
iBake the Eccles cakes for 15-20 mins until just past golden brown and sticky.
iLeave to cool on a rack and enjoy while still warm or cold with a cup of tea.
iIf you prefer, Eccles cakes also go really well served with a wedge of hard, tangy British cheese such as Lancashire or cheddar.
