nNew York cheesecake
cDessert
d52858
iPosition an oven shelf in the middle of the oven.
iPreheat the oven to fan 160C/conventional 180C/gas 4.
iLine the base of a 23cm springform cake tin with parchment paper.
iFor the crust, melt the butter in a medium pan.
iStir in the biscuit crumbs and sugar so the mixture is evenly moistened.
iPress the mixture into the bottom of the pan and bake for 10 minutes.
iCool on a wire rack while preparing the filling.
iFor the filling, increase the oven temperature to fan 200C/conventional 240C/gas 9.
iIn a table top mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, beat the soft cheese at medium-low speed until creamy, about 2 minutes.
iWith the mixer on low, gradually add the sugar, then the flour and a pinch of salt, scraping down the sides of the bowl and the paddle twice.
iSwap the paddle attachment for the whisk.
iContinue by adding the vanilla, lemon zest and juice.
iWhisk in the eggs and yolk, one at a time, scraping the bowl and whisk at least twice.
iStir the 284ml carton of soured cream until smooth, then measure 200ml/7fl oz (just over 3⁄4 of the carton).
iContinue on low speed as you add the measured soured cream (reserve the rest).
iWhisk to blend, but don't over-beat.
iThe batter should be smooth, light and somewhat airy.
iBrush the sides of the springform tin with melted butter and put on a baking sheet.
iPour in the filling - if there are any lumps, sink them using a knife - the top should be as smooth as possible.
iBake for 10 minutes.
iReduce oven temperature to fan 90C/conventional 110C/gas 1⁄4 and bake for 25 minutes more.
iIf you gently shake the tin, the filling should have a slight wobble.
iTurn off the oven and open the oven door for a cheesecake that's creamy in the centre, or leave it closed if you prefer a drier texture.
iLet cool in the oven for 2 hours.
iThe cheesecake may get a slight crack on top as it cools.
iCombine the reserved soured cream with the 142ml carton, the sugar and lemon juice for the topping.
iSpread over the cheesecake right to the edges.
iCover loosely with foil and refrigerate for at least 8 hours or overnight.
iRun a round-bladed knife around the sides of the tin to loosen any stuck edges.
iUnlock the side, slide the cheesecake off the bottom of the tin onto a plate, then slide the parchment paper out from underneath.
