nSticky Toffee Pudding Ultimate
cDessert
d52793
iStone and chop the dates quite small, put them in a bowl, then pour the boiling water over.
iLeave for about 30 mins until cool and well-soaked, then mash a bit with a fork.
iStir in the vanilla extract.
iButter and flour seven mini pudding tins (each about 200ml/7fl oz) and sit them on a baking sheet.
iHeat oven to 180C/fan 160C/gas 4.
iWhile the dates are soaking, make the puddings.
iMix the flour and bicarbonate of soda together and beat the eggs in a separate bowl.
iBeat the butter and sugar together in a large bowl for a few mins until slightly creamy (the mixture will be grainy from the sugar).
iAdd the eggs a little at a time, beating well between additions.
iBeat in the black treacle then, using a large metal spoon, gently fold in one-third of the flour, then half the milk, being careful not to overbeat.
iRepeat until all the flour and milk is used.
iStir the soaked dates into the pudding batter.
iThe mix may look a little curdled at this point and will be like a soft, thick batter.
iSpoon it evenly between the tins and bake for 20-25 mins, until risen and firm.
iMeanwhile, put the sugar and butter for the sauce in a medium saucepan with half the cream.
iBring to the boil over a medium heat, stirring all the time, until the sugar has completely dissolved.
iStir in the black treacle, turn up the heat slightly and let the mixture bubble away for 2-3 mins until it is a rich toffee colour, stirring occasionally to make sure it doesn’t burn.
iTake the pan off the heat and beat in the rest of the cream.
iRemove the puddings from the oven.
iLeave in the tins for a few mins, then loosen them well from the sides of the tins with a small palette knife before turning them out.
iYou can serve them now with the sauce drizzled over, but they’ll be even stickier if left for a day or two coated in the sauce.
iTo do this, pour about half the sauce into one or two ovenproof serving dishes.
iSit the upturned puddings on the sauce, then pour the rest of the sauce over them.
iCover with a loose tent of foil so that the sauce doesn’t smudge (no need to chill).
iWhen ready to serve, heat oven to 180C/fan 160C/gas 4.
iWarm the puddings through, still covered, for 15-20 mins or until the sauce is bubbling.
iServe them on their own, or with cream or custard.
