nStrawberry Rhubarb Pie
cDessert
d53005
iPie Crust:  In a food processor, place the flour, salt, and sugar and process until combined.
imeal (about 15 seconds).
iPour 1/4 cup (60 ml) water in a slow, steady stream, through the feed tube until the dough just holds together when pinched.
iIf necessary, add more water.
iDo not process more than 30 seconds.
iTurn the dough onto your work surface and gather into a ball.
iDivide the dough in half, flattening each half into a disk, cover with plastic wrap, and refrigerate for about one hour before using.
iThis will chill the butter and relax the gluten in the flour.
iAfter the dough has chilled sufficiently, remove one portion of the dough from the fridge and place it on a lightly floured surface.
iRoll the pastry into a 12 inch (30 cm) circle.
i(To prevent the pastry from sticking to the counter and to ensure uniform thickness, keep lifting up and turning the pastry a quarter turn as you roll (always roll from the center of the pastry outwards).
i)  Fold the dough in half and gently transfer to a 9 inch (23 cm) pie pan.
iBrush off any excess flour and trim any overhanging pastry to an edge of 1/2 inch (1.
i5 cm).
iRefrigerate the pastry, covered with plastic wrap, while you make the filling.
iRemove the second round of pastry and roll it into a 13 inch (30 cm) circle.
iUsing a pastry wheel or pizza cutter, cut the pastry into about 3/4 inch (2 cm) strips.
iPlace the strips of pastry on a parchment paper-lined baking sheet, cover with plastic wrap, and place in the refrigerator for about 10 minutes.
iMake the Strawberry Rhubarb Filling: Place the cut strawberries and rhubarb in a large bowl.
iIn a small bowl mix together the cornstarch, sugar, and ground cinnamon.
iRemove the chilled pie crust from the fridge.
iSprinkle about 2 tablespoons of the sugar mixture over the bottom of the pastry crust.
iAdd the remaining sugar mixture to the strawberries and rhubarb and gently toss to combine.
iPour the fruit mixture into the prepared pie shell.
iSprinkle the fruit with about 1 teaspoon of lemon juice and dot with 2 tablespoons of butter.
iRemove the lattice pastry from the refrigerator and, starting at the center with the longest strips and working outwards, place half the strips, spacing about 1 inch (2.
i5 cm) apart, on top of the filling.
i(Use the shortest pastry strips at the outer edges.
i) Then, gently fold back, about halfway, every other strip of pastry.
iTake another strip of pastry and place it perpendicular on top of the first strips of pastry.
iUnfold the bottom strips of pastry and then fold back the strips that weren't folded back the first time.
iLay another strip of pastry perpendicular on top of the filling and then continue with the remaining strips.
iTrim the edges of the pastry strips, leaving a 1 inch (2.
i5 cm) overhang.
iSeal the edges of the pastry strips by folding them under the bottom pastry crust and flute the edges of the pastry.
iBrush the lattice pastry with milk and sprinkle with a little sugar.
iCover and place in the refrigerator while you preheat the oven to 400 degrees F (205 degrees C) and place the oven rack in the lower third of the oven.
iPut a baking sheet, lined with aluminum foil, on the oven rack (to catch any spills.
iPlace the pie plate on the hot baking sheet and bake the pie for about 35 minutes and then, if the edges of the pie are browning too much, cover with a foil ring.
iContinue to bake the pie for about another 10 minutes or until the crust is a golden brown color and the fruit juices begin to bubble.
iRemove the pie from the oven and place on a wire rack to cool for several hours.
iServe at room temperature with softly whipped cream or vanilla ice cream.
iLeftovers can be stored in the refrigerator for about 3 days.
iReheat before serving.
iThis pie can be frozen.
iMakes one 9 inch (23 cm) pie.
