nSummer Pudding
cDessert
d52889
iBring out the juices: Wash fruit and gently dry on kitchen paper – keep strawberries separate.
iPut sugar and 3 tbsp water into a large pan.
iGently heat until sugar dissolves – stir a few times.
iBring to a boil for 1 min, then tip in the fruit (not strawberries).
iCook for 3 mins over a low heat, stirring 2-3 times.
iThe fruit will be softened, mostly intact and surrounded by dark red juice.
iPut a sieve over a bowl and tip in the fruit and juice.
iLine the bowl with cling film and prepare the bread: Line the 1.
i25-litre basin with cling film as this will help you to turn out the pudding.
iOverlap two pieces of cling film in the middle of the bowl as it’s easier than trying to get one sheet to stick to all of the curves.
iLet the edges overhang by about 15cm.
iCut the crusts off the bread.
iCut 4 pieces of bread in half, a little on an angle, to give 2 lopsided rectangles per piece.
iCut 2 slices into 4 triangles each and leave the final piece whole.
iBuild the pud: Dip the whole piece of bread into the juice for a few secs just to coat.
iPush this into the bottom of the basin.
iNow dip the wonky rectangular pieces one at a time and press around the basin’s sides so that they fit together neatly, alternately placing wide and narrow ends up.
iIf you can’t quite fit the last piece of bread in it doesn’t matter, just trim into a triangle, dip in juice and slot in.
iNow spoon in the softened fruit, adding the strawberries here and there as you go.
iLet flavours mingle then serve: Dip the bread triangles in juice and place on top – trim off overhang with scissors.
iKeep leftover juice for later.
iBring cling film up and loosely seal.
iPut a side plate on top and weight down with cans.
iChill for 6 hrs or overnight.
iTo serve, open out cling film then put a serving plate upside-down on top and flip over.
iserve with leftover juice, any extra berries and cream.
