nLamb tomato and sweet spices
cLamb
d52782
iUse pickled vine leaves here, preserved in brine.
iSmall delicate leaves are better than the large bristly ones but, if only large leaves are to hand, then trim them to roughly 12 by 12 cms so that you don't get too many layers of leaves around the filling.
iAnd remove any stalks.
iDrain the preserved leaves, immerse them in boiling water for 10 minutes and then leave to dry on a tea towel before use.
iBasmati rice with butter and pine nuts is an ideal accompaniment.
iCouscous is great, too.
iServes four.
iFirst make the filling.
iPut all the ingredients, apart from the tomatoes, in a bowl.
iCut the tomatoes in half, coarsely grate into the bowl and discard the skins.
iAdd half a teaspoon of salt and some black pepper, and stir.
iLeave on the side, or in the fridge, for up to a day.
iBefore using, gently squeeze with your hands and drain away any juices that come out.
iTo make the sauce, heat the oil in a medium pan.
iAdd the ginger and garlic, cook for a minute or two, taking care not to burn them, then add the tomato, lemon juice and sugar.
iSeason, and simmer for 20 minutes.
iWhile the sauce is bubbling away, prepare the vine leaves.
iUse any torn or broken leaves to line the base of a wide, heavy saucepan.
iTrim any leaves from the fennel, cut it vertically into 0.
i5cm-thick slices and spread over the base of the pan to cover completely.
iLay a prepared vine leaf (see intro) on a work surface, veiny side up.
iPut two teaspoons of filling at the base of the leaf in a 2cm-long by 1cm-wide strip.
iFold the sides of the leaf over the filling, then roll it tightly from bottom to top, in a cigar shape.
iPlace in the pan, seam down, and repeat with the remaining leaves, placing them tightly next to each other in lines or circles (in two layers if necessary).
iPour the sauce over the leaves (and, if needed, add water just to cover).
iPlace a plate on top, to weigh the leaves down, then cover with a lid.
iBring to a boil, reduce the heat and cook on a bare simmer for 70 minutes.
iMost of the liquid should evaporate.
iRemove from the heat, and leave to cool a little - they are best served warm.
iWhen serving, bring to the table in the pan - it looks great.
iServe a few vine leaves and fennel slices with warm rice.
iSpoon the braising juices on top and garnish with coriander.
