nMcSinghs Scotch pie
cLamb
d52880
iHeat a large frying pan and toast the cumin seeds for a few minutes, then set aside.
iHeat the oil in the same pan and fry the onion, garlic, chilli, pepper and a good pinch of salt for around eight minutes, until there is no moisture left.
iRemove from the heat, stir in the toasted cumin seeds, ground mace (or nutmeg) and ground coriander.
iLeave to cool.
iIn a large bowl mix together the minced lamb, white pepper, fresh coriander, and the cooled spiced onion mixture until combined.
iSet aside, covered, in the fridge.
iPreheat the oven to 200C/400F/Gas 6 and generously grease a 20cm/8in diameter loose-bottomed or springform round cake tin with lard.
iTo make the pastry, sift the flour and salt in a large bowl and make a well in the centre.
iPut the milk, lard and 90ml/3fl oz of water in a saucepan and heat gently.
iWhen the lard has melted, increase the heat and bring to the boil.
iPour the boiling liquid into the flour, and use a wooden spoon to combine until cool enough to handle.
iBring together into a ball.
iDust a work surface with flour and, working quickly, knead the dough briefly – it will be soft and moist.
iSet aside a third of the pastry and roll the rest out on a well-floured surface.
iLine the pie dish with the pastry, pressing it right up the sides until it pokes just over the top of the tin.
iAdd the filling into the pastry-lined tin bit by bit.
iAs you reach the top, form a slight peak.
iRoll out the reserved pastry and top the pie with it.
iPinch the edges to seal and trim the excess.
iPoke a hole in the top of the pie and insert a small tube made from aluminium foil to allow steam to escape.
iBrush the top of the pie with a little beaten egg yolk, and bake in the preheated oven for 30 minutes (put a tray on the shelf below to catch any drips).
iThen reduce the temperature to 160C/325F/Gas 3 and cook for a further 1¼ hours until golden-brown.
iLeave to cool completely before refrigerating for two hours, or overnight.
iRun a knife around the edge of the pie, remove from the tin and serve with chutneys, salads or pickles.
