nDuck Confit
cMiscellaneous
d52907
iThe day before you want to make the dish, scatter half the salt, half the garlic and half of the herbs over the base of a small shallow dish.
iLay the duck legs, skin-side up, on top, then scatter over the remaining salt, garlic and herbs.
iCover the duck and refrigerate overnight.
iThis can be done up to 2 days ahead.
iPour the wine into a saucepan that will snugly fit the duck legs in a single layer.
iBrush the salt off the duck legs and place them, skin-side down, in the wine.
iCover the pan with a lid and place over a medium heat.
iAs soon as the wine starts to bubble, turn the heat down to the lowest setting and cook for 2 hours, checking occasionally that the liquid is just barely simmering.
i(If you own a heat diffuser, it would be good to use it here.
i) After 2 hours, the duck legs should be submerged in their own fat and the meat should feel incredibly tender when prodded.
iLeave to cool.
iThe duck legs are now cooked and can be eaten immediately – or you can follow the next step if you like them crisp.
iIf you are preparing ahead, pack the duck legs tightly into a plastic container or jar and pour over the fat, but not the liquid at the bottom of the pan.
iCover and leave in the fridge for up to a month, or freeze for up to 3 months.
iThe liquid you are left with makes a tasty gravy, which can be chilled or frozen until needed.
iTo reheat and crisp up the duck legs, heat oven to 220C/fan 200C/gas 7.
iRemove the legs from the fat and place them, skin-side down, in an ovenproof frying pan.
iRoast for 30-40 mins, turning halfway through, until brown and crisp.
iServe with the reheated gravy, a crisp salad and some crisp golden ptoatoes.
