nThree-cheese souffles
cMiscellaneous
d52912
iHeat oven to 200C/180C fan/ gas 6 and butter 4 small (about 200ml) ramekins.
iSprinkle the Parmesan into the ramekins, turning until all sides are covered.
iPlace the milk and bay leaves in a large saucepan over a gentle heat and bring to the boil.
iTurn off the heat and leave to infuse for 15 mins.
iDiscard the bay leaves, add the butter and flour, and return to a low heat.
iVery gently simmer, stirring continuously with a balloon whisk, for about 6 mins until you get a smooth, thick white sauce.
iMake sure that you get right into the corners of the pan to stop the sauce from catching or becoming lumpy.
iOnce thickened, transfer the sauce to a large bowl and stir in the mustard powder, cayenne pepper, Gruyère and egg yolks until fully combined.
iIn a spotlessly clean bowl and with a clean whisk, beat the egg whites just until peaks begin to form.
iCarefully fold the egg whites into the cheese sauce in three stages making sure you fold, rather than stir, to keep the egg whites light and airy.
iFill the prepared ramekins with the soufflé mix.
iTop each soufflé with a slice of goat’s cheese, then place on a baking tray.
iBake for 20-25 mins or until springy and well risen but cooked through.
iLeave to cool, then run a knife around the edge of each dish and remove the soufflés.
iIf preparing in advance, place soufflés upside down (for neat presentation), on a tray.
iCover tray in cling film.
iChill for a few days or freeze for up to 1 month.
iWhen ready to re-bake, heat oven to 200C/180C fan/gas 6.
iPlace the upside-down soufflés in a shallow baking dish, top with the remaining goat’s cheese slices and pour over the cream (this stops them from drying out when baked for the second time).
iCook for 8-10 mins until golden.
iServe immediately alongside some simply dressed salad.
