nGrilled Mac and Cheese Sandwich
cPasta
d52829
i1. Bring a medium saucepan of generously salted water (you want it to taste like seawater) to a boil.
iAdd the pasta and cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, 8 to 10 minutes, or according to the package directions.
iThe pasta should be tender but still chewy.
i2. While the pasta is cooking, in a small bowl, whisk together the flour, mustard powder, garlic powder, salt, black pepper, and cayenne pepper.
i3. Drain the pasta in a colander.
iPlace the empty pasta pan (no need to wash it) over low heat and add the butter.
iWhen the butter has melted, whisk in the flour mixture and continue to cook, whisking frequently, until the mixture is beginning to brown and has a pleasant, nutty aroma, about 1 minute.
iWatch carefully so it does not scorch on the bottom of the pan.
i4. Slowly whisk the milk and cream into the flour mixture until everything is really well combined.
iCook, whisking constantly, until the sauce is heated through and just begins to thicken, about 2 minutes.
iRemove from the heat.
iGradually add the cheese while stirring constantly with a wooden spoon or silicone spatula and keep stirring until the cheese has melted into the sauce.
iThen stir in the drained cooked pasta.
i5. Line a 9-by-13-inch (23-by-33-centimeter) rimmed baking sheet with parchment paper or aluminum foil.
iCoat the paper or foil with nonstick cooking spray or slick it with butter.
iPour the warm mac and cheese onto the prepared baking sheet and spread it evenly with a spatula.
iCoat another piece of parchment paper with cooking spray or butter and place it, oiled or buttered side down, directly on the surface of the mac and cheese.
iRefrigerate until cool and firm, about 1 hour.
i6. Heat a large cast-iron or nonstick skillet over medium-low heat.
i7. In a small bowl, stir together the 4 tablespoons (55 grams) butter and garlic powder until well blended.
i8. Remove the mac and cheese from the refrigerator and peel off the top layer of parchment paper.
iCarefully cut into 8 equal pieces.
iEach piece will make 1 grilled mac and cheese sandwich.
i(You can stash each individual portion in a double layer of resealable plastic bags and refrigerate for up to 3 days or freeze it for up to 1 month.
i9. Spread 3/4 teaspoon garlic butter on one side of each bread slice.
iPlace half of the slices, buttered-side down, on a clean cutting board.
iTop each with one slice of Cheddar, then 1 piece of the mac and cheese.
i(Transfer from the baking sheet by scooting your hand or a spatula under each piece of mac and cheese and then flipping it over onto a sandwich.
i) Place 1 slice of Jack on top of each.
iFinish with the remaining bread slices, buttered-side up.
i10.
iUsing a wide spatula, place as many sandwiches in the pan as will fit without crowding it.
iCover and cook until the bottoms are nicely browned, about 4 minutes.
iTurn and cook until the second sides are browned, the cheese is melted, and the mac and cheese is heated through, about 4 minutes more.
i11.
iRepeat with the remaining ingredients.
iCut the sandwiches in half, if desired, and serve.
