nPortuguese barbecued pork (Febras assadas)
cPork
d53044
iCut the tenderloins into 5 equal-size pieces leaving the tail ends a little longer.
iTake a clear plastic bag and slip one of the pieces in.
iBash it into an escalope the size of a side-plate with a rolling pin and repeat with the remaining pieces.
iPut the wine, paprika, some salt and pepper and the juice of ½ a lemon in a bowl and add the pork.
iLeave to marinate for 20-30 minutes, while you get your barbecue to the stage where the coals are glowing but there are no flames.
iTo make the chips, fill a basin with cool water and cut the potatoes into 3cm-thick chips.
iSoak them in the water for 5 minutes and then change the water.
iLeave for 5 more minutes.
iDrain and then pat dry on a towel or with kitchen paper.
iHeat the oil in a deep fryer or a deep heavy-based pan with a lid to 130C and lower the chips into the oil (in batches).
iBlanch for 8-10 minutes.
iRemove from the oil and drain well.
iPlace on a tray to cool.
iReheat the oil to 180C (make sure it’s hot or your chips will be soggy) and lower the basket of chips into the oil (again, do this in batches).
iLeave to cook for 2 minutes and then give them a little shake.
iCook for another minute or so until they are well coloured and crisp to the touch.
iDrain well for a few minutes, tip into a bowl and sprinkle with sea salt.
iThe pork will cook quickly so do it in 2 batches.
iTake the pieces out of the marinade, rub them with oil, and drop them onto the barbecue (you could also use a chargrill).
iCook for 1 minute on each side – they may flare up as you do so.
iThis should really be enough time as they will keep on cooking.
iTake them off the barbecue and pile onto a plate.
iRepeat with the remaining batch.
iServe by piling a plate with chips, drop the pork on top of each pile and pouring the juices from the plate over so the chips take up the flavours.
iTop with a spoon of mayonnaise and a wedge of lemon.
