nTonkatsu pork
cPork
d53032
iRemove the large piece of fat on the edge of each pork loin, then bash each of the loins between two pieces of baking parchment until around 1cm in thickness – you can do this using a meat tenderiser or a rolling pin.
iOnce bashed, use your hands to reshape the meat to its original shape and thickness – this step will ensure the meat is as succulent as possible.
iPut the flour, eggs and panko breadcrumbs into three separate wide-rimmed bowls.
iSeason the meat, then dip first in the flour, followed by the eggs, then the breadcrumbs.
iIn a large frying or sauté pan, add enough oil to come 2cm up the side of the pan.
iHeat the oil to 180C – if you don’t have a thermometer, drop a bit of panko into the oil and if it sinks a little then starts to fry, the oil is ready.
iAdd two pork chops and cook for 1 min 30 secs on each side, then remove and leave to rest on a wire rack for 5 mins.
iRepeat with the remaining pork chops.
iWhile the pork is resting, make the sauce by whisking the ingredients together, adding a splash of water if it’s particularly thick.
iSlice the tonkatsu and serve drizzled with the sauce.
