nFish Stew with Rouille
cSeafood
d52918
iTwist the heads from the prawns, then peel away the legs and shells, but leave the tails intact.
iDevein each prawn.
iFry the shells in 1 tbsp oil for 5 mins, until dark pink and golden in patches.
iAdd the wine, boil down by two thirds, then pour in the stock.
iStrain into a jug, discarding the shells.
iHeat the rest of the oil in a deep frying pan or casserole.
iAdd the fennel, onion and garlic, season, then cover and gently cook for 10 mins until softened.
iMeanwhile, peel the potato and cut into 2cm-ish chunks.
iPut into a pan of cold water, bring to the boil and cook for 5 mins until almost tender.
iDrain in a colander.
iPeel a strip of zest from the orange.
iPut the zest, star anise, bay and ½ tsp harissa into the pan.
iFry gently, uncovered, for 5-10 mins, until the vegetables are soft, sweet and golden.
iStir in the tomato purée, cook for 2 mins, then add the tomatoes and stock.
iSimmer for 10 mins until the sauce thickens slightly.
iSeason to taste.
iThe sauce can be made ahead, then reheated later in the day.
iMeantime, scrub the mussels or clams and pull away any stringy beards.
iAny that are open should be tapped sharply on the worktop – if they don’t close after a few seconds, discard them.
iReheat the sauce if necessary, then stir the potato, chunks of fish and prawns very gently into the stew.
iBring back to the boil, then cover and gently simmer for 3 mins.
iScatter the mussels or clams over the stew, then cover and cook for 2 mins more or until the shells have opened wide.
iDiscard any that remain closed.
iThe chunks of fish should flake easily and the prawns should be pink through.
iScatter with the thyme leaves.
iTo make the quick rouille, stir the rest of the harissa through the mayonnaise.
iServe the stew in bowls, topped with spoonfuls of rouille, which will melt into the sauce and enrich it.
iHave some good bread ready, as you’ll definitely want to mop up the juices.
