nKoshari
cVegetarian
d53027
iCook the lentils.
iBring lentils and 4 cups of water to a boil in a medium pot or saucepan over high heat.
iReduce the heat to low and cook until lentils are just tender (15-17 minutes).
iDrain from water and season with a little salt.
i(Note: when the lentils are ready, they should not be fully cooked.
iThey should be only par-cooked and still have a bite to them as they need to finish cooking with the rice).
iNow, for the rice.
iDrain the rice from its soaking water.
iCombine the par-cooked lentils and the rice in the saucepan over medium-high heat with 1 tbsp cooking oil, salt, pepper, and coriander.
iCook for 3 minutes, stirring regularly.
iAdd warm water to cover the rice and lentil mixture by about 1 1/2 inches (you’ll probably use about 3 cups of water here).
iBring to a boil; the water should reduce a bit.
iNow cover and cook until all the liquid has been absorbed and both the rice and lentils are well cooked through (about 20 minutes).
iKeep covered and undisturbed for 5 minutes or so.
iNow make the pasta.
iWhile the rice and lentils are cooking, make the pasta according to package instructions by adding the elbow pasta to boiling water with a dash of salt and a little oil.
iCook until the pasta is al dente.
iDrain.
iCover the chickpeas and warm in the microwave briefly before serving.
iMake the crispy onion topping.
iSprinkle the onion rings with salt, then toss them in the flour to coat.
iShake off excess flour.
iIn a large skillet, heat the cooking oil over medium-high heat, cook the onion rings, stirring often, until they turn a nice caramelized brown.
iOnions must be crispy, but not burned (15-20 minutes).
