nRoasted Eggplant With Tahini, Pine Nuts, and Lentils
cVegetarian
d52816
iFor the Lentils: Adjust oven rack to center position and preheat oven to 450°F to prepare for roasting eggplant.
iMeanwhile, heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a medium saucepan over medium heat until shimmering.
iAdd carrots, celery, and onion and cook, stirring, until softened but not browned, about 4 minutes.
iAdd garlic and cook, stirring, until fragrant, about 30 seconds.
iAdd lentils, bay leaves, stock or water, and a pinch of salt.
iBring to a simmer, cover with the lid partially ajar, and cook until lentils are tender, about 30 minutes.
i(Top up with water if lentils are at any point not fully submerged.
i) Remove lid, stir in vinegar, and reduce until lentils are moist but not soupy.
iSeason to taste with salt and pepper, cover, and keep warm until ready to serve.
iFor the Eggplant: While lentils cook, cut each eggplant in half.
iScore flesh with the tip of a paring knife in a cross-hatch pattern at 1-inch intervals.
iTransfer to a foil-lined rimmed baking sheet, cut side up, and brush each eggplant half with 1 tablespoon oil, letting each brushstroke be fully absorbed before brushing with more.
iSeason with salt and pepper.
iPlace a rosemary sprig on top of each one.
iTransfer to oven and roast until completely tender and well charred, 25 to 35 minutes.
iRemove from oven and discard rosemary.
iTo Serve: Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil and pine nuts in a medium skillet set over medium heat.
iCook, tossing nuts frequently, until golden brown and aromatic, about 4 minutes.
iTransfer to a bowl to halt cooking.
iStir half of parsley and rosemary into lentils and transfer to a serving platter.
iArrange eggplant halves on top.
iSpread a few tablespoons of tahini sauce over each eggplant half and sprinkle with pine nuts.
iSprinkle with remaining parsley and rosemary, drizzle with additional olive oil, and serve.
