nSmoky Lentil Chili with Squash
cVegetarian
d52784
iBegin by roasting the squash.
iSlice it into thin crescents and drizzle with a little oil and sprinkle with sea salt.
iI added a fresh little sage I had in the fridge, but it’s unnecessary.
iRoast the squash a 205 C (400 F) for 20-30 minutes, flipping halfway through, until soft and golden.
iLet cool and chop into cubes.
iMeanwhile, rinse the lentils and cover them with water.
iBring them to the boil then turn down to a simmer and let cook (uncovered) for 20-30 minutes, or until tender.
iDrain and set aside.
iWhile the lentils are cooking heat the 1 Tbsp.
iof oil on low in a medium pot.
iAdd the onions and leeks and sauté for 5 or so minutes, or until they begin to soften.
iAdd the garlic next along with the cumin and coriander, cooking for a few more minutes.
iAdd the remaining spices – paprika, cinnamon, chilli, cocoa, Worcestershire sauce, salt, and oregano.
iNext add the can of tomatoes, the water or stock, and carrots.
iLet simmer, covered, for 20 minutes or until the veg is tender and the mixture has thickened up.
iYou’ll need to check on the pot periodically for a stir and a top of of liquid if needed.
iAdd the lentils and chopped roasted squash.
iLet cook for 10 more minutes to heat through.
iServe with sliced jalapeno, lime wedges, cilantro, green onions, and cashew sour cream.
i1 tsp.
iBring some water to the boil, and use it to soak the cashews for at least four hours.
iAlternatively, you can use cold water and let the cashews soak overnight, but I’m forgetful/lazy, so often use the boil method which is much faster.
iAfter the cashews have soaked, drain them and add to a high speed blender.
iBegin to puree, slowly adding about 1/2 cup fresh water, until a creamy consistency is reached.
iYou may need to add less or more water to reach the desired consistency.
iAdd a pinch of sea salt and vinegar (or lemon juice).
